3. quaedam loca, &c This state· ment is very obscure, and would appear as if Tacitus was describing something which he imperfectly understood. Itis not clear whether the colouring was on the exterior or interior surfaces, but it is most probable that' the ‘quaedam loca’ were certain porticus or chambers in- side, and that these were plastered over with coloured earth or earths of such purity and brighmess as to correspond in some sort to the Roman wall decorations (such as are seen at Pompeii). The ‘earth’ can hardly be (as some think) mere white chalk, ,which could hardly be said ‘imitari picturam,’ but is probably some kind of ochre‚ and os more than one colour, so arranged as to approach in some sort to a design. ‘Imitari’ has the sense of substitution, as inVerg. G. 3, 380, Aen. 11, 894, &c., and ‘ picturam' is not ‘ a picture’ (in which sense ‘picturas‘ would probably have been used) but ‘the art

4. solent, probably not with the same subject as ‘inlinunt,’ but rather ‘there are some who’ &c., like ‘ gerunt’ (c. 17, 2). The ruder tribes os the north appear to be meant.

5. specus. Pliny (19. 1, a, 9) speaks of such not as dwellings but spiuning places (‘ in Germania defossi atque snb terra id opus agunt ’), and old laws give evidence of such workplaces for women still existing in the middle ages (see Ms. cited by SS.), as well as storehouses. Subterraneau dwellings for shelter in winter are described among other northern nations (cp. Verg. G. 3, 376), similar to the pit dwellings of which remains are found in England and else· where, or to those of the present Eskimanx.
